ntury France explores how fiction and related writing on olfaction meet, permeate, and illuminate one another. The book examines medical tracts, letters, manuscripts, posters, print advertisements, magazine articles, perfume manuals, etiquette books, interviews, and encounters with fragrant materials themselves. Cheryl Krueger explores how the olfactory language of a novel or poem conveys the distinctiveness of a text, its unique relationship to language, its style, and its ways of engaging the reader: its signature scent. Shedding light on the French perfume culture that we know today, Perfume on the Page in Nineteenth-Century France follows the scent trails that ultimately challenge us to read perfume and literature in new ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrench literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aOdors in literature. 0aPerfumes in literature. 0aSmell in literature. 0aWomen in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh  aBalzac.  aBaudelaire.  aFlaubert.  aFrench history.  aFrench perfume.  aGoncourt.  aParis.  aRachilde.  aZola.  acosmetics.  afashion.  anineteenth-century French literature.  aolfaction.  aolfactory.  asenses.  asillage.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079736740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754658840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487546588423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487546588/original  a978-3-11-079736-7  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles